nt Protest and Progressive Ethos at the 2011 Wisconsin Labour Rallies -- t12. Occupy Wall Street: Carnival Against Capital? Carnivalesque as Protest Sensibility -- t13. Subversion through Performance: Performance Activism in London -- t14. Spain’s Indignados and the Mediated Aesthetics of Non-violence -- t15 The Poetics of Indignation in Greece: Anti-austerity Protest and Accountability -- tAbout the Contributors -- tWeb Sources for Figures -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPublished in Association with the Institute for the Study of Muslim CivilisationsExplores the aesthetic dimensions of the Arab Spring and the protest movements that followedFrom Egypt to India, and from Botswana to London, worker, youth and middle class rebellions have taken on the political and bureaucratic status quo and the privilege of small, wealthy and often corrupt elites at a time when the majority can no longer earn a decent wage.A remarkable feature of the protests from the Arab Spring onwards has been the salience of images, songs, videos, humour, satire and dramatic performances. This book explores the central role the aesthetic played in energising the mass mobilisations of young people, the disaffected, the middle classes, the apolitical silent majority, as well as enabling solidarities and alliances among democrats, workers, trade unions, civil rights activists and opposition parties.Comparing the North African and Middle Eastern uprisings with protest movements such as Occupy, the authors bring to bear an anthropological and sociological approach from a variety of perspectives, illuminating the debate by drawing on a wide array of disciplinary expertise.Key FeaturesIncludes over 150 colour illustrations showing how visual media is used in protest movements across the globeShares perspectives from political, media, visual, economic and linguistic anthropology, and the anthropology of work, art, social organisation and social movementLooks at the use of social networking and new media technologies such as TwitterCase studies includeProtests about regime change in Tunisia, Egypt, Syria, Libya, Bahrain, Yemen and RussiaCorruption in IndiaThe demise of the welfare state in Spain, Israel and GreeceThe living wage in Botswana and WisconsinThe financial crisis and corporate greed and the Occupy movement in British and American citiesPublished in association with The Aga Khan University Institute for the Study of Muslim Civilisations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAestheticsxPolitical aspects. 0aArab Spring, 2010-. 0aOccupy movement. 0aProtest movements in mass media. 0aProtest movementsxPolitical aspects. 0aProtest movements. 0aVisual communicationxPolitical aspects. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAl-Eryani, Hazim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAryani, Rayman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaton, Steven C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherstich, Igor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarlough, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatriel, Tamar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLivio, Oren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinney, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPostill, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSabea, Hanan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSerafini, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://